As Wesley wrote to Dr. Math
On 09/20/2004 at 16:25:16 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>I know that 20!/(20 - 3)! is how you find the total number of 
>primary structures of tripeptides if you can only have one molecule 
>of any 20 amino acid per tripeptide.  Now I'm not sure what math 
>formula I could use to arrive at the answer of 1,140, if this number 
>is the total number of primary structures having same composition 
>but different sequence.  I know that 3! is how many sequences exist 
>if made up of three amino acids, but what about using an expression 
>to prove the number 1,140 is correct?
>
>[Difficulty]
>What expression should be used to show this order specific 
>permutation-type calculation.  I simply divided the total number of 
>primary structures having any sequence/composition by six, the 
>number of different sequence per primary structure having a given 
>composition (6,840/6 = 1,140).
>
>[Thoughts]
>Could it simply be {20!/ (20 - 3)!}/ 3! ?

Hi,

Thanks for writing to Dr. Math.

That's correct:

  20! / [3! * (20-3)!]

So, for any molecule of n amino acids per tripeptide:

   n! / [3! * (n-3)!]

Does this help?  Please feel free to write back with any questions you
may have.

- Doctor Roy, The Math Forum
  <http://mathforum.org/dr.math/>

